You are simulating a realistic inpatient doctor–patient conversation for a single hospital admission.
You MUST follow these rules:

1) Use only the facts provided in the EHR packet. Do NOT invent diagnoses, symptoms, test results, medications, procedures, timelines, or outcomes.
2) Every clinically factual statement MUST be supported by an explicit evidence citation using the provided EIDs (e.g., "Evidence: [LAB#000123, RAD#000004]").
3) If the EHR packet does not contain a fact, say you do not know or that it is not documented.
4) Produce a chronological conversation spanning the full admission, from admission through discharge.
5) Use RELATIVE time only (e.g., "H+03:15", "HospitalDay2 09:40"). Do not mention calendar dates or years.
6) Discharge summaries are provided; treat them as post-hoc summaries that help you maintain coherence, but do not reveal discharge outcomes before they occur in the chronology.
7) Output must be valid JSON, conforming exactly to the output schema described in the user message. No extra keys.

Initial evaluation showed low but stable blood pressure with normal oxygenation, a normal EKG, and a chest X-ray without acute pulmonary process. She was monitored on telemetry without arrhythmias, and transthoracic echocardiography showed normal biventricular systolic function and no structural cause of syncope. Laboratory studies revealed significant hypercalcemia (total calcium up to 12.7 mg/dL with elevated ionized calcium), elevated PTH in the setting of ESRD, and chronic macrocytosis with mild leukopenia and stable platelets. She underwent hemodialysis with no ultrafiltration, which improved her calcium and renal indices while avoiding further hypotension. A cosyntropin stimulation test demonstrated adequate adrenal reserve, ruling out adrenal insufficiency. CT head for new left-sided headaches showed no acute intracranial process, and abdominal ultrasound for nausea showed no acute hepatobiliary pathology but innumerable bilateral renal cysts. Blood cultures remained negative, and she stayed afebrile. Her presyncope and hypotension were attributed to dialysis-related volume shifts and medication effects; diltiazem was discontinued, and midodrine was initiated to support blood pressure. Nausea improved with antiemetics, and headaches were managed symptomatically. She was discharged home in stable condition, ambulatory and hemodynamically at her low baseline, with continued HAART and dialysis-related medications, new midodrine and prochlorperazine, and instructions for outpatient follow-up including vascular studies for leg pain.","problem_list":[{"problem":"Presyncope and hypotension, likely related to hemodialysis volume shifts and medication effects","status_at_discharge":"Blood pressure remained in her low baseline systolic 90–100 mmHg range, afebrile, with negative orthostatics, normal echocardiogram, no arrhythmias on telemetry, and improved symptoms; Dr. ___ was present throughout the\nprocedure.\n\nSEDATION:  Conscious sedation with divided doses of intravenous fentanyl (100\nmcg) and Versed (2 mg) over the total intraservice time of 1 hour and 15\nminutes during which the patient's hemodynamic status was continuously\nmonitored by a trained radiology nurse.\n\nCONTRAST:  Approximately 15 ml of Optiray 320 intravenous contrast.\n\nPROCEDURE:  Informed consent was obtained from the patient after explaining\nthe benefits, risks, and alternatives to the procedure.  The patient was\nplaced supine on the imaging table in the interventional suite.  A\npreprocedure timeout and huddle were performed per ___ protocol.\n\nThe left neck was prepped and draped in the usual sterile manner.  Ultrasound\nimages demonstrated a patent left internal jugular vein.  Access was obtained\nunder ultrasound guidance.  A guidewire was placed through the access needle;\nhowever, the wire could not be advanced beyond the central left subclavian\nvein.  At this point, the needle was exchanged for a microsheath over the\nguidewire.  Contrast was injected through the microsheath under fluoroscopic\nguidance which demonstrated complete thrombosis of the central left subclavian\nvein.\n\nThe right neck was then interrogated with ultrasound which demonstrated a\npatent right internal jugular vein.  The right neck was prepped and draped in\nthe usual sterile manner.  Access was again obtained through the right\ninternal jugular vein under ultrasound guidance.  A guidewire was placed\nthrough the needle and the needle was exchanged for a microsheath.  Contrast\nwas injected through the microsheath which demonstrated prominent collateral\nveins; however, the right subclavian and SVC were not visualized.\n\nAfter discussion with the patient's primary team including Dr. ___\nand the nephrologist, Dr. ___, a decision was made to attempt a\ntunneled femoral line the next day given the patient's continued low-grade\nfevers.\n\nIMPRESSION:  Unsuccessful attempt of placement of IJ HD catheter. Timeout was performed as per ___\nprotocol.  The patient was placed supine on the imaging table in the\ninterventional suite.\n\nUnder aseptic conditions and sonographic guidance, a micropuncture needle was\nplaced in the right common femoral vein at the level of the midfemoral head. \nA 0.018 wire was advanced through the needle and into the IVC.  The needle was\nexchanged over the wire for 4.5 ___ microsheath.  Inner cannula and wire\nwere removed to facilitate placement of a 0.035 ___ wire, which was advanced\ninto the right atrium.  Appropriate measurements were made.  Attention was\ndirected to the right anterior thigh at an appropriate distance from the\nvenotomy site.  Skin was infiltrated with adequate amounts of 1% lidocaine.  A\nsmall skin incision was made.  The proposed tunnel site was subcutaneously\ninfiltrated with a mixture of 1% lidocaine and epinephrine.  A new 15.5 ___\n50-cm (tip-to-cuff) hemodialysis catheter was connected to a blunt metallic\ndissector and tunneled subcutaneously from the skin incision site to exit at\nthe puncture site overlying venotomy.  Microsheath was removed to perform\nserial dilatation with 8, 12 and 14 ___ dilators under fluoroscopy,\neventually leading to placement of a 16 ___ peel-away sheath.  The wire and\ninner dilator were removed to facilitate placement of the tunneled catheter. \nSheath was peeled away.  Catheter tip was confirmed under fluoroscopy to be in\nthe right atrium.  Catheter was secured by 0 silk sutures.  Puncture site was\nsutured with subcuticular ___ Vicryl suture.  Sites were appropriately\ndressed.  The patient tolerated the procedure.
